        <p>Let's look at another example:</p>
        <example>
            <title>Blood Type A</title>

            <p>The probability of having blood type A is .4. Choose 4 people at random and let X be
                the number with blood type A. </p>
            <p>X is a binomial random variable with n = 4 and p = .4.</p>
            <p>As a review, let's first find the probability distribution of X the long way:
                construct an interim table of all possible outcomes in S, the corresponding values
                of X, and probabilities. Then construct the probability distribution table for
                X.</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image090.gif" alt="The probability distribution
table, with three columns, &quot;S,&quot; &quot;X,&quot; and &quot;Probability.&quot; Here is the
data in the table, given in row format (S: X, Probability):
                NNNN: 0, .4^0 &times; .6^4;
                NNNA: 1, .4^1 &times; .6^3;
                NNAN: 1, .4^1 &times; .6^3;
                NANN: 1, .4^1 &times; .6^3;
                ANNN: 1, .4^1 &times; .6^3;
                NNAA: 2, .4^2 &times; .6^2;
                NANA: 2, .4^2 &times; .6^2;
                NAAN: 2, .4^2 &times; .6^2;
                ANNA: 2, .4^2 &times; .6^2;
                ANAN: 2, .4^2 &times; .6^2;
                AANN: 2, .4^2 &times; .6^2;
                NAAA: 3, .4^3 &times; .6^1;
                ANAA: 3, .4^3 &times; .6^1;
                AANA: 3, .4^3 &times; .6^1;
                AAAN: 3, .4^3 &times; .6^1;
                AAAA: 4, .4^4 &times; .6^0;"/>
            <p>As usual, the addition rule lets us combine probabilities for each possible value of
                X:</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image091.gif" alt="A table with two columns,
labeled &quot;X,&quot; and &quot;Probability.&quot; Here is the data, in row format (X, Probability):
                0: (1) &times; .4^0 &times; .6^4 = .1296;
                1: (4) &times; .4^1 &times; .6^3 = .3456;
                2: (6) &times; .4^2 &times; .6^2 = .3456;
                3: (4) &times; .4^3 &times; .6^1 = .1536;
                4: (1) &times; .4^4 &times; .6^0 = .0256;"/>
            <p>Now let's apply the formula for the probability distribution of a binomial random
                variable, and see that by using it, we get exactly what we got the long way.</p>
            <p>Recall<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T203331-0500" content=","?>
                that the general formula for the probability distribution of a binomial random
                variable with n trials and probability of success p is:</p>
