        <p>Here is another interesting example.</p>
        <example>
            <title>Choosing Numbers at Random</title>

            <p>Do people really choose numbers at random?</p>
            <p>Each student in a group of 15 students is asked to each pick a number from
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T211826-0500"?>1<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T211824-0500" content="one"?>
                to
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T211830-0500"?>20<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T211828-0500" content="twenty"?>
                completely at random. 3 of the 15 happen to pick the number
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212123-0500"?>7<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212121-0500" content="seven"?>
                (this is a probability of .20). Is this an improbably high proportion to choose a
                particular number?</p>
            <p>If the selections are truly random, then each number from
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212132-0500"?>1<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212131-0500" content="one"?>
                to
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212136-0500"?>20<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212134-0500" content="twenty"?>,
                including
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212141-0500"?>7<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212139-0500" content="seven"?>,
                has probability p = 1/20 = .05 of being selected. The number of trials is n = 15.
                The probability of at least 3 successes in 15 trials, when each trial has
                probability of success .05, can be found by applying the binomial formula.</p>
            <p>To make the notation
                easier<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T211912-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                we will use a shorthand
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T211931-0500"?>notation
                <?oxy_insert_end?>for the number of possible outcomes with x successes out of n.
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>!</m:mo>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>!</m:mo>
                            <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                            <m:mo>!</m:mo>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:mfrac>
                </m:math> will be written as: <m:math overflow="scroll">
                    <m:msubsup>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi/>
                            <m:mn>x</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>n</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:msubsup>
                    <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                </m:math> .</p>
            
            
