            <p>where all remaining terms after the first
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212008-0500"?>3<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212006-0500" content="three"?>
                are less than .0001. The probability of at least 3 out of 15 people picking
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212100-0500"?>7<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212058-0500" content="seven"?>,
                when choosing at random from the numbers
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212052-0500"?>1<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212050-0500" content="one"?>
                to
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212056-0500"?>20<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212054-0500" content="twenty"?>,
                is only .0362. Thus, 3 out of 15 is rather improbably high. People may think they
                are choosing at random, but in fact they tend to favor certain numbers, like the
                number
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212109-0500"?>7<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212108-0500" content="seven"?>.</p>
