        <p>Now let's look at some truly practical applications of binomial random variables.</p>
        <example>
            <title>Airline Flights</title>
            <p>Past studies have shown that 90% of the booked passengers actually arrive for a
                flight. Suppose that a small shuttle plane has 45 seats. We will assume that
                passengers arrive independently of each other.
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212316-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>This
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212319-0500" content="is a bit of an "?>assumption<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212256-0500"?>
                is not really accurate,<?oxy_insert_end?> since not all people travel
                alone<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212339-0500"?>, but
                we'll use it for the purposes of our experiment)<?oxy_insert_end?>.</p>
            <p>Many times airlines "<em>overbook</em>" flights. This means that the<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212505-0500" content="y"?>
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212508-0500"?>airline
                <?oxy_insert_end?>sell<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212512-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>
                more tickets than there are seats
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212413-0500"?>o<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212412-0500" content="i"?>n
                the plane. This is due to the fact that sometimes passengers don't show
                up<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212525-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                and
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212533-0500" content="they fly "?>the
                plane <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212556-0500"?>must be
                flown <?oxy_insert_end?>with empty seats. However, if they do overbook, they run the
                risk of having more passengers than seats. So, some passengers may be unhappy. They
                also have the extra expense of putting
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212439-0500"?>those
                passengers<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212438-0500" content="them"?>
                on another flight and possibly supplying lodging.</p>
            <p>With these risks in mind, the airline decides to sell more than 45 tickets. If they
                wish to keep the probability of having more than 45 passengers
                show<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212631-0500" content="ing"?> up
                to <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212638-0500"?>get on the
                flight to less
                than<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212652-0500" content="be under"?>
                0.05, how many tickets should they sell?</p>
            <p>This is a binomial random variable that
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212706-0500"?>represents<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212709-0500" content="counts"?>
                the number of passengers that show up for the flight. It has p = 0.90, and n to be
                determined.</p>
            <p>Suppose the<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212725-0500" content="y"?>
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212727-0500"?>airline
                <?oxy_insert_end?>sell<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212731-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>
                50 tickets. Now we have n = 50 and p = 0.90. We want to know P(X >
                45)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212739-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                which is 1 - P(X ≤ 45) = 1 - 0.57 or 0.43. Obviously, all the details of this
                calculation were not
                shown<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212753-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                since <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212800-0500"?>a
                statistical <?oxy_insert_end?>technology
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212807-0500"?>package
                <?oxy_insert_end?>was
                used<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212811-0500"?> to
                calculate the answer<?oxy_insert_end?>. This is certainly more than 0.05, so
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212830-0500"?>the
                airline<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212829-0500" content="we"?>
                must sell fewer seats. </p>
            <p>If we reduce the number of tickets sold, we should be able to reduce this
                probability. We have calculated the probabilities in the following table:</p>
            <table rowstyle="alternating">
                <tr>
                    <th># tickets sold</th>
                    <th>P(X > 45)</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>50</td>
                    <td>0.43</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>49</td>
                    <td>0.26</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>48</td>
                    <td>0.13</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>47</td>
                    <td>0.04</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>46</td>
                    <td>0.008</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <p>From this
                table<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212852-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                we can see that
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212904-0500"?>by<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212908-0500" content="if we"?>
                sell<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212911-0500"?>ing<?oxy_insert_end?>
                47 tickets<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212915-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212916-0500"?>the
                airline<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212918-0500" content="we"?>
                can reduce the probability that
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212924-0500"?>it<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212925-0500" content="we"?>
                will have more passengers show up than
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212932-0500"?>there are
                <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212936-0500" content="we have"?>
                seats to
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212941-0500" content="under"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T212942-0500"?>less
                than<?oxy_insert_end?> 5%.</p>
            <p>Note: For practice in finding binomial probabilities, you may wish to verify one or
                more of the results from the table above.</p>
        </example>
